<p>The idea wasn't born in a boardroom. It was forged in a furnace. In 1980, Nash owed $500,000 at interest rates climbing toward 23%. His home had been burglarized, his brother had died suddenly, and his infant granddaughter was fighting cancer. During many sleepless nights — on his knees at 3 and 4 a.m. — the answer came to him "like a baseball bat across the eyes."</p>
<p>He realized he already owned whole life policies that gave him contractual access to capital at 5% to 8%. The system was already there. He just couldn't see it because he was looking at things the way everyone else did.</p>
